THIS POST IS NO LONGER ACCURATE. PLEASE VISIT WWW.WCSDPA.ORG for UPDATED INFO

Update on Spectator Guidelines for WCSD Sports Events

The Warren County School District will be updating its safety procedures related to spectators at sporting events based on new information released by Governor Tom Wolfe this afternoon (9/2/20).

The Governor's previous guidance limited sports-related activities at the PK-12 level to student-athletes, coaches, officials, and staff only. The new guidance, which will allow spectators, still imposes limits on total attendance. District administrative staff will review the new guidance and work with PIAA and other groups to develop a new procedure for the fall 2020 season.

post_text:
Spectator Guidelines for WCSD Sports Events

*** UPDATE 9./2/20 ***
The information in this post is currently inaccurate as a result of new information received today from Governor Wolf ***

Please be aware that the district must follow certain requirements to continue to offer sports to our students. Therefore, NO spectators will be permitted on school property during scheduled athletic events. This applies to both the home and visiting teams.

If spectators do not leave as required, the game will be stopped and the individual(s) will be asked to leave. Anyone refusing to leave will result in the game being remaining paused while local law enforcement is called to escort the offender(s) off the premises.

The district will be exploring options on how to stream sporting events on Facebook or some other video outlet and hopes to have something in place in the near future.

post_text:
Internet Outage and High Call Volumes Impacting WCSD Phone System (8/31/20)

The WCSD is aware of the issues related to its phone systems. We have been working with our provider and have been informed that the issue is related to both high call volumes at the schools and the recent internet outage that took place over the weekend.

While we don't have an ETA on when the phone systems will be working normally, we can tell you that the phone "trunk" at each building is currently only able to handle a maximum of thirteen calls at a time.

The 13 call limit is for both incoming/outgoing calls.

We appreciate the inconvenience that this imposes on families as you are trying to finalize the educational needs for your students and ask for your patience as the district's provider works on a resolution.

'Check Before You Choose' Cyber Charter Comparison Tool

The Warren County School District administration understands that the COVID-19 pandemic has forced many families to make difficult educational decisions as we prepare to reopen schools for 2020-21. For some, one of those decisions is whether a cyber charter school is an option for their child.

Over 90% of Pennsylvania school districts offer a virtual learning program, including the WCSD. We would like to provide a resource to help you make the best decision for your child and family. The link below is to the 'Check Before You Choose' website, provided by PA Schools Work.

https://paschoolswork.org/check/

Check Before You Choose provides an outline of the questions parents may want to ask about a cyber charter program before enrolling while also providing a breakdown on cyber charter performance against that of your local school district.

If you have any questions about the WCSD's Virtual Academy, please call 814-723-0574 or https://www.wcsdpa.org/Domain/61.

Children's Health Insurance Program (CHIP) Notice

CHIP covers uninsured children and teens up to age 19 – and no family earns too much to qualify. With more than 124,000 uninsured children in Pennsylvania, this is great news for families!

CHIP provides quality, comprehensive health insurance for routine doctor visits, prescriptions, dental, eye care, eyeglasses, mental health, and much more. CHIP covers uninsured kids who are not eligible for Medical Assistance. For most families, CHIP is free – for others, it is low cost.

See the flyer for more information!

post_text:
I know there is a lot of information and discussion being generated by the Governor’s statements about athletics today. I also know there is a considerable amount of frustration around the inconsistent information regarding cheer, band and ability for parents to attend athletic events.

The PIAA has shared a press release letting us know that they will be meeting tomorrow and they will have another press release tomorrow afternoon.

In an effort to be perfectly clear, at this time, the District has not cancelled any athletic activities. We have worked hard to make sure we are providing opportunities for our students to participate in the activities they love. We will have to see what PIAA shares tomorrow. Stay tuned.

Amy Stewart

With the increased need for food due to COVID-19, Second Harvest is continuing to expand its services to reach families in need of food within northwest Pennsylvania, including Warren county.

Pre-registration is required, so please follow the instructions on the flyer below.

post_text:
To each of the 2020 graduates of the Warren County School District.

You, your family, and your friends have been waiting for this day. When you started your senior year of high school, you probably never suspected the changes that would come just a few short months before final exams. Then came the disruptions to your lives due to the attempts to slow and prevent the spread of COVID-19. Those steps caused many anxiety and concern, and reduced the opportunities that you had to enjoy and celebrate your senior year. For that, I share your disappointment.

You are, however, each young and resilient, and you come from families and communities that care for and support you. I hope that you all can take this experience and build from it. Use it to grow into the extraordinary people that you can be.

From all of us at the Warren County School District, congratulations, and best of luck to you in all you do!

Sincerely,

Superintendent Amy Stewart and the entire WCSD Family

Updated Summer Food Sites, Meals, and Hours as of June 8, 2020

The Warren County School District has committed to continuing the Summer Food Service Program through at least June 30, 2020. On Monday, June 8, 2020, meal distribution will move to Monday, Wednesday, and Friday; some sites and meal service times have changed as well

Meals will be available for multiple days: Monday will be for Monday/Tuesday meals, Wednesday for Wednesday/Thursday, and Friday for Friday through Sunday.

The changes will take place on Monday, June 8, 2020. Please visit the district website at www.wcsdpa.org for the updated list of sites and hours of operation, as well as a letter that provides more detail on the changes.

Parent Technology Survey - 5/21/20

The Warren County School District has created another technology survey to help us to better understand the technologies currently available in our students’ homes as we begin planning for the 2020-21 school year.

There are ten (10) questions to answer, and we ask that one parent/guardian complete a survey for EVERY student in the home.

Click https://forms.office.com/Pages/ResponsePage.aspx?id=5H8HhE0j_EmCsJyTTTqn4jHHh_dN3TRAgSPdNTVFc6pUNzBNREtDWEZOVlRSU09DSVo0RU1FSVNRNC4u for the survey, which will also be available on the district and school Facebook pages and websites.

For those who do not have internet or Facebook access, paper copies of the survey will again be made available at each of our food serving sites beginning on Tuesday, May 26, 2020. If you cannot make it to a food serving site or do not have the means to complete the survey online, you may also call your child’s building administrator, and they will complete the survey for you via a telephone call.

State Announces Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer Program (P-EBT)

The federal Families First Coronavirus Response Act of 2020 provides temporary benefits, referred to as Pandemic Electronic Benefit Transfer (P-EBT), to families of school-aged children who would receive free or reduced-priced meals if school was in session.

For each day school is closed, families of school-aged children certified as free or reduced eligible will receive the equivalent of the free high rate for lunch and the severe need rate for breakfast. Specifically, a family will receive $5.70 for each eligible school-aged child in their family for each day school has been closed since March 16, 2020.

P-EBT is administered by the state but the WCSD wants to share as much information with its parents as possible to best position those in need to receive assistance. Please visit www.wcsdpa.org for much more detail on P-EBT, including a link to an FAQ and actions taken by the WCSD. The P-EBT announcement is under 'News'.

May is Mental Health Awareness Month

The Pennsylvania Department of Human Services has established a statewide Support & Referral Helpline to counsel Pennsylvanians struggling with anxiety and other challenging emotions due to the COVID-19 emergency. The Helpline is staffed by skilled and compassionate caseworkers who are available 24/7 and able to refer callers to community-based resources that can further help to meet individual needs.

The toll-free, round-the-clock support line is available at 1-855-284-2494. For TTY, dial 724-631-5600.

WCSD Announces Free Training to Help Parents Balance Student Learning & Behavior

During these uncertain times of COVID-19, the Warren County School District will provide free training to serve parents of children (birth -21) and all disability areas. Our expert professionals will provide these training sessions to help parents balance learning and behavior at home during the COVID-19 pandemic. Training will be available using FB Live video chats, online platform, and/or phone consultation.

Training sessions are as follows:
- Promoting Independence in Activities of Daily Living
* Monday, May 18, 2020, at 5:00 PM

- Speech and Language Department Parent Training
* Ongoing

Please visit the WCSD website Announcement section, available at www.wcsdpa.org, for the link to the PDF that provides additional details for each session, as well as how to access the training sessions themselves.

Like and follow the WCSD PT & OT Facebook Page as well for more useful information. A link to that page was posted here on May 6, 2020.

Phase 3A of the WCSD Continuity of Education Plan Announced

Phase 3A of the district’s Continuity of Education Plan starts on April 28th.

Phase 3A materials will not be graded for Grades K-5. More information about Phase 3B for elementary will be ready soon.

For Grades 6-12, Phase 3A online application-based projects will be available by April 28th. Students working offline will receive their packets that day at their bus stops following a two-hour delay bus schedule. Those who don’t ride a bus may pick up their packets at their home school.

Phase 3A projects are graded and are the only grade for the fourth marking period for Grades 6-12.

Online projects are due Wednesday, May 20th. Offline projects will be picked up on Thursday, May 21st at bus stops using a two-hour delay bus schedule.

Projects submitted after Friday, May 22nd will result in a late grade in the fourth marking period.

Students are encouraged to reach out to teachers or schools for any needed support.

WCSD COVID-19 Phase 2 Begins April 16th

The Warren County School District and Warren County Career Center are entering Phase 2 of the Continuity of Education Plan. Teachers are sending Phase 2 online enrichment and review activities this week.

For students working offline, Phase 2 enrichment and review activities will be delivered by bus on Thursday, April 16th, 2020. As with Phase 1, buses will be following a two-hour delay schedule.

Students may pick up their offline packet at their assigned bus stop. Any student who does not ride a bus may pick up their packet at their home building.

Phase 2 runs from Thursday, April 16th, 2020 to Monday, April 28th, 2020. Teachers, School Counselors, and Support Staff will be reaching out to you to provide assistance, as needed. If you have any further questions or concerns, please contact your building administrator.

WCSD Continuity of Education Plan Available for Review

The WCSD administration presented its Continuity of Education Plan to the district's Curriculum, Instruction, and Assessment Committee on Monday, April 6, 2020. The plan is available for viewing and/or download from the WCSD website under the News section, at www.wcsdpa.org.

The Continuity Plan is a tool to assist the district in the process of planning, implementing, and assessing learning activities during the COVID-19 school closure. This plan is the basis for detailed phases developed to guide implementation.

WCSD families and employees are encouraged to review the document to better understand the district's plans to move forward. Please remember that the plan remains fluid as the district adjusts to the ongoing situation and directives from various government agencies.

Eisenhower Instructors receive STEM Grants

Eric Shotts and Jennifer Morrison, Instructors at Eisenhower Middle High School, each received STEM grant funding from FirstEnergy/Penelec. The grants were for classroom projects to introduce power distribution through a power grid: compare the alternative energy sources of Wind Generation and solar panels to traditional power generation, and display the advanced solar home kit and activities in the hallway or Elementary STEM Lab.

Great work Mr. Shotts and Mrs. Morrison!

Nambour State College
January 12 at 7:54 PM ·

Online Safety. Do you know what your children are watching online and who they are messaging?

National Online Safety have put together some fantastic resources for parents and carers about social media apps, online games and trending issues so they can have informed discussions with their children. All resources, plus much more can be accessed from the National Online Safety website:

https://nationalonlinesafety.com/resources/wake-up-wednesday/

post_text:
Eric Mineweaser, WCSD Director of Curriculum, Instruction, and Assessment; holds a $2,590 grant check from the Pennsylvania Association of Rural and Small Schools. The grant will provide funds for the creation of Vex Robotics competition teams at Eisenhower Middle High School.

A Vex Robotics match is pictured to Mr. Mineweaser's right. Matches are taking place between schools all over northwestern PA as part of an effort to provide students with more STEM activities.

Additional grant funding has been received from other sources to establish teams at the other WCSD high schools as well.

Some gasoline from the tractor used for plowing was spilled early this morning in the garage at Youngsville Elementary School, spurring some reports of smelling gas this morning. Emergency Management and the Fire Department have been on-site and have assured us everything is safe.

We thank them for their assistance and for making sure our students and staff are safe.

post_text:
Kindergarten Registration 2020-21

IMPORTANT! The Kindergarten Admission Age has changed. Beginning with the 2020/2021 school year, and continuing thereafter, in order to meet the earliest admission age for the District’s kindergarten program, the student must be five years old on or before July 1.

No early admission to Kindergarten shall be permitted.

Dates and times for Kindergarten registration are available by on the district website in the Announcement section. Click the link below for the district webpage.
https://www.wcsdpa.org/Domain/8

Applicant must have a first-aid background, understand the care and prevention of athletic injuries, and understand training and conditioning procedures. Previous knowledge/coaching and/or participation (postsecondary) in the sport will be considered in the selection process.
